					<msContents>
						<summary>

						<p>Slab setup in front of the Hanuman temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Tribhuvanamalla [Vikramāditya VI] 1099 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>The first portion of this record [about 17 lines] is completely damaged and even the next portion is also damaged. But some information can be culled out from the extant portion of engraving. It records a gift of 55 <hi rend="italic">mattar</hi> land, an oil mill for burning perpetual lamp, 6 <hi rend="italic">mattar</hi> land for flower garden and an additional 2 <hi rend="italic">mattar</hi> land made probably by Vaṁṇēśvarāji. Probably the gift was made to a temple the information of which is lost.</p>						

						<p>This portion of the record is dated in Chālukya Vikrama year 24, Pramādi, Kārttika, śu. 12 Thursday. It corresponds with 1099 A.D., October 28 [Friday] f.d.t. 77.</p>						

						</summary>
